Rule: PGM508
Severity: INFO
Description: Duplicate or redundant index detected (prefix of another index)

PGM508 — Duplicate/redundant indexes

What it detects:
A CREATE INDEX that produces an index whose columns are an exact
duplicate or a leading prefix of another index on the same table.

Why it matters:
Redundant indexes waste disk space, slow writes (every INSERT/UPDATE/
DELETE must maintain all indexes), and add vacuum overhead. A btree
index on (a, b) already serves lookups on (a) — a separate index on
(a) provides no additional query capability.

Example (bad):
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_customer ON orders (customer_id);
CREATE INDEX idx_orders_customer_date ON orders (customer_id, created_at);
-- idx_orders_customer is redundant: idx_orders_customer_date covers it.

Fix:
Drop the shorter index:
DROP INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_customer;

Does NOT fire when:
- The shorter (potentially redundant) index is UNIQUE — it enforces a
constraint the longer one doesn't.
- Either index is partial (has a WHERE clause).
- Either index has expression entries.
- The indexes use different access methods (btree vs GIN vs ...).

The check uses catalog_after so indexes created later in the same
migration file are visible.
